answerText: Cryovolcanism [or Cryovolcano; prompt on Ice Volcano or anything implying a volcano that is cold][10] In 2005, Cassini detected Cryovolcanism during a flyby of this non-Titan moon of Saturn.The pure water ejected in its cryovolcanic eruption has led scientists to believe there could be an ocean underneath the surface.

subject: Science
question: Question: These phenomena originate on cold bodies when tidal interactions heats up internal water and ammonia sufficiently to volatilize them. For 10 points each: [10] Name this cold form of eruption, usually observed on moons which has been hypothesized to happen on Pluto and other Kuiper Belt objects. It resembles a geyser more than its earthly namesake.
